    "body": "For my workflow: I tend to keep batches of code I'm working on together in lines, to avoid cluttering the UI with too many single-line cells.\n\nCurrently, I'm working on some code with one cell near the top containing parameters that later cells use. I've been fiddling with some test cases, and changing those parameters, and then jumping around to subsequent cells to test little chunks of code and how they end up behaving after the parameter changes.\n\nI was not aware that the express purpose of ctrl-enter is to delete or replace the code after running. Coming from Mathematica, running a cell in place does just that, and only that, if I remember correctly. Also, if ctrl-enter is designed to this behavior, I think it should be made a bit more explicit. The only difference when you hit \"ctrl-m h\" between shift- and ctrl-enter is \"in place\", so I got weirded out when the cells kept selecting. It feels like a macro I didn't write added on top of what I thought the basic functionality would be.\n"
  },
